⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
When designing this fireplace we had 3 details in mind:
___
Durability - This is important for both the hearth and surrounding material. We chose a honed natural stone hearth complemented by a custom patinated steel surround. Both materials are safe to withstand high temperatures. 
____
Functionality - We were tasked with creating a new look for the fireplace and TV area. The homeowners loved the idea of metal and stone as well as recessing the TV into the metal for a streamlined look. 
____
Design - The overall design was meant to create a focal point and ultimately ended up making the space feel more generous. Pairing a natural stone with the custom patinated finish was intended to be a close color match. Backlighting was incorporated to create depth and ambiance. 📸: @dallasandharrisphoto⁠

At one of our favorite Denver Design Center showrooms @cpabystark choosing quality carpet!
___
Here’s what you should pay attention to: 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Fiber content - natural fibers like 100% wool are my favorite when selecting carpet. Linen and silk can add luster and shine but when it comes to extra durability? Wool can’t be beat. Areas that receive less traffic can better handle a mix of materials.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Color fastness - a quality fabric should have good color retention, meaning it won’t fade quickly when washed or exposed to sunlight.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Durability & wear resistance - high-traffic areas and upholstery fabric should be chosen for their resistance to wear, stains, and fading. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
When you’re choosing from a large amount of carpet options, taking the time to understand the characteristics of each one and how they perform can help you make more informed decisions.

I’m sharing my secrets to selecting art & decor for a space!

First off, art and decor should complement the activities that take place within the space. A vibrant, colorful piece may fit in a living room, but a primary bedroom may call for something a bit more serene. 

Consider the scale and proportion of the artwork and decor in relation to the space it’s in. Oversized pieces can make a bold statement, but a gallery wall may be better for creating a visual interest. 

A mix of mediums and textures can add depth and diversity in design. Combine paintings, sculptures, and other decorative elements to create a visually rich environment.

I’m sharing 3 things you need to know before starting an interior design project ⬇️

The first is a solid understanding of the budget allocated for the project. This includes furniture, materials, design firm fees, and any additional funds for potential setbacks and unexpected problems. 

Collect images and inspiration photos that complement your style and aesthetics. Think about how you currently use your space and how you plan to use it in the future. Do you require any specific functionality? Do you need the design to be flexible for your evolving lifestyle? 

Establish open communication with your design team. Clearly express your expectations, concerns, and requirements for the project before they break ground. This is a collaborative process and a mutual understanding helps the project run smoothly.
